issue.title: #685 Support build problem service message for TeamCity

body:
We did this by design, but I agree that returning zero is a bug. We will need to decide what to return if _no_ assemblies can be run as well as what to return if only _some_ assemblies fail to load.

I don't think we should need a special message in this case, provided we return an error code. At least, I hope not. :-)
Special messages will allow users to get more information about problem

rename.from: Build problem service message for TeamCity
rename.to: In the some cases when tests cannot be started NUnit returns exit code "0"

[18:56:07][Step 4/6]

It looks like there is sufficient info given in the console output that we could simply define a code to return when some assembly cannot be loaded. Since an rc > 0 is defined to mean the number of failing test cases, this should be one of our negative codes.

I think all the codes are already defined, we just stopped returning them between 2.6.4 and 3.0.

NUnit 2.x returned -2 and -100 in response to exceptions it caught. By design, we no longer throw those exceptions but instead return a TestResult that includes the error information. The console runner should analyze the result and return the appropriate error code. 

In fact, it's already analyzing the result in order to display the errors, so this shouldn't be too hard.

I spotted another error in the output posted by @NikolayPianikov - there is a separate error line displayed for the nunit project file. That's erroneous because the project file is only marked as a failure because of an error at the assembly level. If it's convenient, we should fix this at the same time. Otherwise, another issue can be filed.
